[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] If the more constrained model (i.e., the null hypothesis) is supported by the observed data, the two likelihoods should not differ by more than sampling error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Thus the likelihood-ratio test tests whether this ratio is significantly different from one, or equivalently whether its natural logarithm is significantly different from zero.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The likelihood-ratio test, also known as **Wilks test**, is the oldest of the three classical approaches to hypothesis testing, together with the Lagrange multiplier test and the Wald test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] In fact, the latter two can be conceptualized as approximations to the likelihood-ratio test, and are asymptotically equivalent.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] In the case of comparing two models each of which has no unknown parameters, use of the likelihood-ratio test can be justified by the Neyman–Pearson lemma.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The lemma demonstrates that the test has the highest power among all competitors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Suppose that we have a statistical model with parameter space $\Theta$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] A null hypothesis is often stated by saying that the parameter $\theta$ lies in a specified subset $\Theta _{0}$ of $\Theta$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The alternative hypothesis is thus that $\theta$ lies in the complement of $\Theta _{0}$ , i.e. in $\Theta ~\backslash ~\Theta _{0}$ , which is denoted by $\Theta _{0}^{\text{c}}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] where the quantity inside the brackets is called the likelihood ratio.
