[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] As all likelihoods are positive, and as the constrained maximum cannot exceed the unconstrained maximum, the likelihood ratio is bounded between zero and one and the likelihood ratio test statistic between 0 and infinity.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Multiplying by −2 ensures mathematically that (by Wilks' theorem) $\lambda _{\text{LR}}$ converges asymptotically to being χ²-distributed if the null hypothesis happens to be true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The finite-sample distributions of likelihood-ratio statistics are generally unknown.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The likelihood-ratio test requires that the models be nested – i.e. the more complex model can be transformed into the simpler model by imposing constraints on the former's parameters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Many common test statistics are tests for nested models and can be phrased as log-likelihood ratios or approximations thereof: e.g. the *Z*-test, the *F*-test, the *G*-test, and Pearson's chi-squared test; for an illustration with the one-sample *t*-test, see below.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] If the models are not nested, then instead of the likelihood-ratio test, there is a generalization of the test that can usually be used: for details, see *relative likelihood*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] ${\begin{aligned}H_{0}&:&\theta =\theta _{0},\\H_{1}&:&\theta =\theta _{1}.\end{aligned}}$ In this case, under either hypothesis, the distribution of the data is fully specified: there are no unknown parameters to estimate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Some older references may use the reciprocal of the function above as the definition.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Thus, the likelihood ratio is small if the alternative model is better than the null model.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The likelihood ratio is a function of the data x ; therefore, it is a statistic, although unusual in that the statistic's value depends on a parameter, $\theta$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The likelihood-ratio test rejects the null hypothesis if the value of this statistic is too small.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] How small is too small depends on the significance level of the test, i.e. on what probability of Type I error is considered tolerable (Type I errors consist of the rejection of a null hypothesis that is true).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The numerator corresponds to the likelihood of an observed outcome under the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The denominator corresponds to the maximum likelihood of an observed outcome, varying parameters over the whole parameter space.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The numerator of this ratio is less than the denominator; so, the likelihood ratio is between 0 and 1.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Low values of the likelihood ratio mean that the observed result was much less likely to occur under the null hypothesis as compared to the alternative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] High values of the statistic mean that the observed outcome was nearly as likely to occur under the null hypothesis as the alternative, and so the null hypothesis cannot be rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] The following example is adapted and abridged from Stuart, Ord & Arnold (1999, §22.2).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Suppose that we have a random sample, of size n, from a population that is normally-distributed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Both the mean, μ, and the standard deviation, σ, of the population are unknown.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] We want to test whether the mean is equal to a given value, *μ*0 .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Thus, our null hypothesis is *H*0: *μ* = *μ*0 and our alternative hypothesis is *H*1: *μ* ≠ *μ*0 .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] With some calculation (omitted here), it can then be shown that $\lambda _{LR}=n\ln \left(1+{\frac {t^{2}}{n-1}}\right)$ where t is the t-statistic with *n* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] Hence we may use the known exact distribution of *t**n*−1 to draw inferences.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] If the distribution of the likelihood ratio corresponding to a particular null and alternative hypothesis can be explicitly determined then it can directly be used to form decision regions (to sustain or reject the null hypothesis).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/likelihood-ratio-test] In most cases, however, the exact distribution of the likelihood ratio corresponding to specific hypotheses is very difficult to determine.
