[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The **null hypothesis** (often denoted ${\textstyle H_{0}}$ ) is the claim in scientific research that the effect being studied does not exist.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The null hypothesis can also be described as the hypothesis in which no relationship exists between two sets of data or variables being analyzed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the null hypothesis is true, any experimentally observed effect is due to chance alone, hence the term "null".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In contrast with the null hypothesis, an alternative hypothesis (often denoted $H_{A}$ or $H_{1}$ ) is developed, which claims that a relationship does exist between two variables.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The null hypothesis and the *alternative hypothesis* are types of conjectures used in statistical tests to make statistical inferences, which are formal methods of reaching conclusions and separating scientific claims from statistical noise.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The statement being tested in a test of statistical significance is called the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The test of significance is designed to assess the strength of the evidence against the null hypothesis, or a statement of 'no effect' or 'no difference'.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The statement that is being tested against the null hypothesis is the alternative hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A statistical significance test starts with a random sample from a population.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the sample data are consistent with the null hypothesis, then you do not reject the null hypothesis; if the sample data are inconsistent with the null hypothesis, then you reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the alternative hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Given the test scores of two random samples, one of men and one of women, does one group score better than the other?
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A stronger null hypothesis is that the two samples come from populations with equal variances and shapes of their respective distributions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Any hypothesis that specifies the population distribution completely.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] For such a hypothesis the sampling distribution of any statistic is a function of the sample size alone.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] specify the population distribution completely.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Example: A hypothesis specifying a normal distribution with a specified mean and an unspecified variance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The simple/composite distinction was made by Neyman and Pearson.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Those specifying a parameter range or interval.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Fisher required an exact null hypothesis for testing (see the quotations below).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A one-tailed hypothesis is said to have **directionality**.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Fisher's original (lady tasting tea) example was a one-tailed test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The probability of guessing all cups correctly was the same as guessing all cups incorrectly, but Fisher noted that only guessing correctly was compatible with the lady's claim.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The null hypothesis is a default hypothesis that a quantity to be measured is zero (null).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Typically, the quantity to be measured is the difference between two situations.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] For instance, trying to determine if there is a positive proof that an effect has occurred or that samples derive from different batches.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The null hypothesis is generally assumed to remain possibly true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Multiple analyses can be performed to show how the hypothesis should either be rejected or excluded e.g. having a high confidence level, thus demonstrating a statistically significant difference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] This is demonstrated by showing that zero is outside of the specified confidence interval of the measurement on either side, typically within the real numbers.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Failure to exclude the null hypothesis (with any confidence) does not logically confirm or support the (unprovable) null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] (When it is proven that something is e.g. bigger than *x*, it does not necessarily imply it is plausible that it is smaller or equal than *x*; it may instead be a poor quality measurement with low accuracy.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Confirming the null hypothesis is two-sided would amount to positively proving it is bigger or equal than 0 *and* to positively proving it is smaller or equal than 0; this is something for which infinite accuracy is needed as well as exactly zero effect, neither of which normally are realistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The used confidence level does absolutely certainly not correspond to the likelihood of null at failing to exclude; in fact in this case a high used confidence level *expands* the still plausible range.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A non-null hypothesis can have the following meanings, depending on the author a) a value other than zero is used, b) some margin other than zero is used and c) the "alternative" hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Testing (excluding or failing to exclude) the null hypothesis provides evidence that there are (or are not) statistically sufficient grounds to believe there *is* a relationship between two phenomena (e.g., that a potential treatment has a non-zero effect, either way).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Testing the null hypothesis is a central task in statistical hypothesis testing in the modern practice of science.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] There are precise criteria for excluding or not excluding a null hypothesis at a certain confidence level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The confidence level should indicate the likelihood that much more and better data would still be able to exclude the null hypothesis on the same side.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The concept of a null hypothesis is used differently in two approaches to statistical inference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In the significance testing approach of Ronald Fisher, a null hypothesis is rejected if the observed data are significantly unlikely to have occurred if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In this case, the null hypothesis is rejected and an alternative hypothesis is accepted in its place.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the data are consistent with the null hypothesis statistically possibly true, then the null hypothesis is not rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In neither case is the null hypothesis or its alternative proven; with better or more data, the null may still be rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] This is analogous to the legal principle of presumption of innocence, in which a suspect or defendant is assumed to be innocent (null is not rejected) until proven guilty (null is rejected) beyond a reasonable doubt (to a statistically significant degree).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In the hypothesis testing approach of Jerzy Neyman and Egon Pearson, a null hypothesis is contrasted with an alternative hypothesis, and the two hypotheses are distinguished on the basis of data, with certain error rates.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] It is used in formulating answers in research.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Statistical inference can be done without a null hypothesis, by specifying a statistical model corresponding to each candidate hypothesis, and by using model selection techniques to choose the most appropriate model.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] (The most common selection techniques are based on either Akaike information criterion or Bayes factor).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Hypothesis testing requires constructing a statistical model of what the data would look like if chance or random processes alone were responsible for the results.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The hypothesis that chance alone is responsible for the results is called the *null hypothesis*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The model of the result of the random process is called the *distribution under the null hypothesis*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The obtained results are compared with the distribution under the null hypothesis, and the likelihood of finding the obtained results is thereby determined.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Hypothesis testing works by collecting data and measuring how likely the particular set of data is (assuming the null hypothesis is true), when the study is on a randomly selected representative sample.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The null hypothesis assumes no relationship between variables in the population from which the sample is selected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the data-set of a randomly selected representative sample is very unlikely relative to the null hypothesis (defined as being part of a class of sets of data that are rarely observed), the experimenter rejects the null hypothesis, concluding it (probably) is false.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] This class of data-sets is usually specified via a test statistic, which is designed to measure the extent of apparent departure from the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the data do not contradict the null hypothesis, then only a weak conclusion can be made: namely, that the observed data set provides insufficient evidence against the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Nevertheless, if at this point the effect appears likely and/or large enough, there may be an incentive to further investigate, such as running a bigger sample.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] For instance, a certain drug may reduce the risk of having a heart attack.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Possible null hypotheses are "this drug does not reduce the risk of having a heart attack" or "this drug has no effect on the risk of having a heart attack".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The test of the hypothesis consists of administering the drug to half of the people in a study group as a controlled experiment.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the data show a statistically significant change in the people receiving the drug, the null hypothesis is rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] There are many types of significance tests for one, two or more samples, for means, variances and proportions, paired or unpaired data, for different distributions, for large and small samples; all have null hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Rejection of the null hypothesis is *not necessarily* the real goal of a significance tester.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] An adequate statistical model may be associated with a failure to reject the null; the model is adjusted until the null is not rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The numerous uses of significance testing were well known to Fisher who discussed many in his book written a decade before defining the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A statistical significance test shares much mathematics with a confidence interval.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A result is often significant when there is confidence in the sign of a relationship (the interval does not include 0).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Whenever the sign of a relationship is important, statistical significance is a worthy goal.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] This also reveals weaknesses of significance testing: A result can be significant without a good estimate of the strength of a relationship; significance can be a modest goal.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A weak relationship can also achieve significance with enough data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Reporting both significance and confidence intervals is commonly recommended.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The varied uses of significance tests reduce the number of generalizations that can be made about all applications.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The choice of the null hypothesis is associated with sparse and inconsistent advice.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Fisher mentioned few constraints on the choice and stated that many null hypotheses should be considered and that many tests are possible for each.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The variety of applications and the diversity of goals suggests that the choice can be complicated.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In many applications the formulation of the test is traditional.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A familiarity with the range of tests available may suggest a particular null hypothesis and test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Formulating the null hypothesis is not automated (though the calculations of significance testing usually are).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] David Cox said, "How [the] translation from subject-matter problem to statistical model is done is often the most critical part of an analysis".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A statistical significance test is intended to test a hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] If the hypothesis summarizes a set of data, there is no value in testing the hypothesis on that set of data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Example: If a study of last year's weather reports indicates that rain in a region falls primarily on weekends, it is only valid to test that null hypothesis on weather reports from any *other* year.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Testing hypotheses suggested by the data is circular reasoning that proves nothing; It is a special limitation on the choice of the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A routine procedure is as follows: Start from the scientific hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A complex case example is as follows: The gold standard in clinical research is the randomized placebo-controlled double-blind clinical trial.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] But testing a new drug against a (medically ineffective) placebo may be unethical for a serious illness.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Testing a new drug against an older medically effective drug raises fundamental philosophical issues regarding the goal of the test and the motivation of the experimenters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The standard "no difference" null hypothesis may reward the pharmaceutical company for gathering inadequate data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] "Difference" is a better null hypothesis in this case, but statistical significance is not an adequate criterion for reaching a nuanced conclusion that requires a good numeric estimate of the drug's effectiveness.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A "minor" or "simple" proposed change in the null hypothesis ((new vs old) rather than (new vs placebo)) can have a dramatic effect on the utility of a test for complex non-statistical reasons.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The choice of null hypothesis (*H*0) and consideration of directionality (see "one-tailed test") is critical.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Consider the question of whether a tossed coin is fair (i.e. that on average it lands heads up 50% of the time) and an experiment where you toss the coin 5 times.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A possible result of the experiment that we consider here is 5 heads.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Let outcomes be considered unlikely with respect to an assumed distribution if their probability is lower than a significance threshold of 0.05.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A potential null hypothesis implying a one-tailed test is "this coin is not biased toward heads".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Indeed, with a fair coin the probability of this experiment outcome is 1/25 = 0.031, which would be even lower if the coin were biased in favour of tails.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Therefore, the observations are not likely enough for the null hypothesis to hold, and the test refutes it.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Since the coin is ostensibly neither fair nor biased toward tails, the conclusion of the experiment is that the coin is biased toward heads.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Alternatively, a null hypothesis implying a two-tailed test is "this coin is fair".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] This one null hypothesis could be examined by looking out for either too many tails or too many heads in the experiments.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The outcomes that would tend to refute this null hypothesis are those with a large number of heads or a large number of tails, and our experiment with 5 heads would seem to belong to this class.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] However, the probability of 5 tosses of the same kind, irrespective of whether these are head or tails, is twice as much as that of the 5-head occurrence singly considered.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Hence, under this two-tailed null hypothesis, the observation receives a probability value of 0.063.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Hence again, with the same significance threshold used for the one-tailed test (0.05), the same outcome is not statistically significant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Therefore, the two-tailed null hypothesis is preserved in this case, not supporting the conclusion reached with the single-tailed null hypothesis, that the coin is biased toward heads.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] This example illustrates that the conclusion reached from a statistical test may depend on the precise formulation of the null and alternative hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Fisher said, "the null hypothesis must be exact, that is free of vagueness and ambiguity, because it must supply the basis of the 'problem of distribution,' of which the test of significance is the solution", implying a more restrictive domain for *H*0.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] According to this view, the null hypothesis must be numerically exact—it must state that a particular quantity or difference is equal to a particular number.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] In classical science, it is most typically the statement that there is *no effect* of a particular treatment; in observations, it is typically that there is *no difference* between the value of a particular measured variable and that of a prediction.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Most statisticians believe that it is valid to state direction as a part of null hypothesis, or as part of a null hypothesis/alternative hypothesis pair.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] However, the results are not a full description of all the results of an experiment, merely a single result tailored to one particular purpose.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] For example, consider an *H*0 that claims the population mean for a new treatment is an improvement on a well-established treatment with population mean = 10 (known from long experience), with the one-tailed alternative being that the new treatment's mean > 10.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] To overcome any possible ambiguity in reporting the result of the test of a null hypothesis, it is best to indicate whether the test was two-sided and, if one-sided, to include the direction of the effect being tested.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The statistical theory required to deal with the simple cases of directionality dealt with here, and more complicated ones, makes use of the concept of an unbiased test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The directionality of hypotheses is not always obvious.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The explicit null hypothesis of Fisher's Lady tasting tea example was that the Lady had no such ability, which led to a symmetric probability distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The one-tailed nature of the test resulted from the one-tailed alternate hypothesis (a term not used by Fisher).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The null hypothesis became implicitly one-tailed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The logical negation of the Lady's one-tailed claim was also one-tailed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] (Claim: Ability > 0; Stated null: Ability = 0; Implicit null: Ability ≤ 0).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Pure arguments over the use of one-tailed tests are complicated by the variety of tests.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Some tests (for instance the χ2 goodness of fit test) are inherently one-tailed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Some probability distributions are asymmetric.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The traditional tests of 3 or more groups are two-tailed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Advice concerning the use of one-tailed hypotheses has been inconsistent and accepted practice varies among fields.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The greatest objection to one-tailed hypotheses is their potential subjectivity.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] A non-significant result can sometimes be converted to a significant result by the use of a one-tailed hypothesis (as the fair coin test, at the whim of the analyst).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The flip side of the argument: One-sided tests are less likely to ignore a real effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] One-tailed tests can suppress the publication of data that differs in sign from predictions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Objectivity was a goal of the developers of statistical tests.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] It is a common practice to use a one-tailed hypothesis by default.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] However, "If you do not have a specific direction firmly in mind in advance, use a two-sided alternative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] One alternative to this advice is to use three-outcome tests.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] It eliminates the issues surrounding directionality of hypotheses by testing twice, once in each direction and combining the results to produce three possible outcomes.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Variations on this approach have a history, being suggested perhaps 10 times since 1950.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Disagreements over one-tailed tests flow from the philosophy of science.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] While Fisher was willing to ignore the unlikely case of the Lady guessing all cups of tea incorrectly (which may have been appropriate for the circumstances), medicine believes that a proposed treatment that kills patients is significant in every sense and should be reported and perhaps explained.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Poor statistical reporting practices have contributed to disagreements over one-tailed tests.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Statistical significance resulting from two-tailed tests is insensitive to the sign of the relationship; Reporting significance alone is inadequate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] "The treatment has an effect" is the uninformative result of a two-tailed test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] "The treatment has a beneficial effect" is the more informative result of a one-tailed test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] "The treatment has an effect, reducing the average length of hospitalization by 1.5 days" is the most informative report, combining a two-tailed significance test result with a numeric estimate of the relationship between treatment and effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] Explicitly reporting a numeric result eliminates a philosophical advantage of a one-tailed test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/null-hypothesis] The history of the null and alternative hypotheses has much to do with the history of statistical tests.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In null-hypothesis significance testing, the ***p*-value** is the probability of obtaining test results at least as extreme as the result actually observed, under the assumption that the null hypothesis is correct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] A very small *p*-value means that such an extreme observed outcome would be very unlikely *under the null hypothesis*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Even though reporting *p*-values of statistical tests is common practice in academic publications of many quantitative fields, misinterpretation and misuse of p-values is widespread and has been a major topic in mathematics and metascience.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] That said, a 2019 task force by ASA has issued a statement on statistical significance and replicability, concluding with: "*p*-values and significance tests, when properly applied and interpreted, increase the rigor of the conclusions drawn from data".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In statistics, every conjecture concerning the unknown probability distribution of a collection of random variables representing the observed data X in some study is called a *statistical hypothesis*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] If we state one hypothesis only and the aim of the statistical test is to see whether this hypothesis is tenable, but not to investigate other specific hypotheses, then such a test is called a null hypothesis test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] As our statistical hypothesis will, by definition, state some property of the distribution, the null hypothesis is the default hypothesis under which that property does not exist.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The null hypothesis is typically that some parameter (such as a correlation or a difference between means) in the populations of interest is zero.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Our hypothesis might specify the probability distribution of X precisely, or it might only specify that it belongs to some class of distributions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Often, we reduce the data to a single numerical statistic, e.g., T , whose marginal probability distribution is closely connected to a main question of interest in the study.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-value is used in the context of null hypothesis testing in order to quantify the statistical significance of a result, the result being the observed value of the chosen statistic T .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The lower the *p*-value is, the lower the probability of getting that result if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] A result is said to be *statistically significant* if it allows us to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] All other things being equal, smaller *p*-values are taken as stronger evidence against the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Loosely speaking, rejection of the null hypothesis implies that there is sufficient evidence against it.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Different tests of the same null hypothesis would be more or less sensitive to different alternatives.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] However, even if we do manage to reject the null hypothesis for all 3 alternatives, and even if we know that the distribution is normal and variance is 1, the null hypothesis test does not tell us which non-zero values of the mean are now most plausible.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-value is the probability under the null hypothesis of obtaining a real-valued test statistic at least as extreme as the one obtained.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Consider an observed test-statistic t from unknown distribution T .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Then the *p*-value p is what the prior probability would be of observing a test-statistic value at least as "extreme" as t if null hypothesis $H_{0}$ were true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The 0.05 value (equivalent to 1/20 chances) was originally proposed by Ronald Fisher in 1925 in his famous book entitled "Statistical Methods for Research Workers".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Different *p*-values based on independent sets of data can be combined, for instance using Fisher's combined probability test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-value is a function of the chosen test statistic T and is therefore a random variable.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] If the null hypothesis fixes the probability distribution of T precisely (e.g. $H_{0}:\theta =\theta _{0},$ where $\theta$ is the only parameter), and if that distribution is continuous, then when the null-hypothesis is true, the *p*-value is uniformly distributed between 0 and 1.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Regardless of the truth of the $H_{0}$ , the *p*-value is not fixed; if the same test is repeated independently with fresh data, one will typically obtain a different *p*-value in each iteration.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Usually only a single *p*-value relating to a hypothesis is observed, so the *p*-value is interpreted by a significance test, and no effort is made to estimate the distribution it was drawn from.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] When a collection of *p*-values are available (e.g. when considering a group of studies on the same subject), the distribution of significant *p*-values is sometimes called a *p*-curve.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] A *p*-curve can be used to assess the reliability of scientific literature, such as by detecting publication bias or *p*-hacking.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In parametric hypothesis testing problems, a *simple or point hypothesis* refers to a hypothesis where the parameter's value is assumed to be a single number.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In contrast, in a *composite hypothesis* the parameter's value is given by a set of numbers.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] When the null-hypothesis is composite (or the distribution of the statistic is discrete), then when the null-hypothesis is true the probability of obtaining a *p*-value less than or equal to any number between 0 and 1 is still less than or equal to that number.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In other words, it remains the case that very small values are relatively unlikely if the null-hypothesis is true, and that a significance test at level $\alpha$ is obtained by rejecting the null-hypothesis if the *p*-value is less than or equal to $\alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In this example, that would be the *Z*-statistic belonging to the one-sided one-sample *Z*-test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] For each possible value of the theoretical mean, the *Z*-test statistic has a different probability distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In these circumstances, the *p*-value is defined by taking the least favorable null-hypothesis case, which is typically on the border between null and alternative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] This definition ensures the complementarity of p-values and alpha-levels: $\alpha =0.05$ means one only rejects the null hypothesis if the *p*-value is less than or equal to $0.05$ , and the hypothesis test will indeed have a *maximum* type-1 error rate of $0.05$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-value is widely used in statistical hypothesis testing, specifically in null hypothesis significance testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In this method, before conducting the study, one first chooses a model (the null hypothesis) and the alpha level *α* (most commonly 0.05).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] After analyzing the data, if the *p*-value is less than *α*, that is taken to mean that the observed data is sufficiently inconsistent with the null hypothesis for the null hypothesis to be rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] However, that does not prove that the null hypothesis is false.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-value does not, in itself, establish probabilities of hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Rather, it is a tool for deciding whether to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] According to the ASA, there is widespread agreement that *p*-values are often misused and misinterpreted.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] One practice that has been particularly criticized is accepting the alternative hypothesis for any *p*-value nominally less than 0.05 without other supporting evidence.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Another concern is that the *p*-value is often misunderstood as being the probability that the null hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] *p*-values and significance tests also say nothing about the possibility of drawing conclusions from a sample to a population.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Some statisticians have proposed abandoning *p*-values and focusing more on other inferential statistics, such as confidence intervals, likelihood ratios, or Bayes factors, but there is heated debate on the feasibility of these alternatives.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] At the same time, the use of *p*-values has also been defended as a useful statistical tool that should not be abandoned.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Others have suggested to remove fixed significance thresholds and to interpret *p*-values as continuous indices of the strength of evidence against the null hypothesis, although these proposals in themselves have been criticized.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Yet others suggested to report alongside *p*-values the prior probability of a real effect that would be required to obtain a false positive risk (i.e. the probability that there is no real effect) below a pre-specified threshold (e.g.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] That said, in 2019 a task force by ASA had convened to consider the use of statistical methods in scientific studies, specifically hypothesis tests and *p*-values, and their connection to replicability.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] It states that "Different measures of uncertainty can complement one another; no single measure serves all purposes", citing *p*-value as one of these measures.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] They also stress that *p*-values can provide valuable information when considering the specific value as well as when compared to some threshold.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In general, it stresses that "*p*-values and significance tests, when properly applied and interpreted, increase the rigor of the conclusions drawn from data".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] A test statistic is the output of a scalar function of all the observations.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] This statistic provides a single number, such as a *t*-statistic or an *F*-statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] As such, the test statistic follows a distribution determined by the function used to define that test statistic and the distribution of the input observational data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] For the important case in which the data are hypothesized to be a random sample from a normal distribution, depending on the nature of the test statistic and the hypotheses of interest about its distribution, different null hypothesis tests have been developed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Thus computing a *p*-value requires a null hypothesis, a test statistic (together with deciding whether the researcher is performing a one-tailed test or a two-tailed test), and data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Even though computing the test statistic on given data may be easy, computing the sampling distribution under the null hypothesis, and then computing its cumulative distribution function (CDF) is often a difficult problem.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Today, this computation is done using statistical software, often via numeric methods (rather than exact formulae), but, in the early and mid 20th century, this was instead done via tables of values, and one interpolated or extrapolated *p*-values from these discrete values.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Rather than using a table of *p*-values, Fisher instead inverted the CDF, publishing a list of values of the test statistic for given fixed *p*-values; this corresponds to computing the quantile function (inverse CDF).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] As an example of a statistical test, an experiment is performed to determine whether a coin flip is fair (equal chance of landing heads or tails) or unfairly biased (one outcome being more likely than the other).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Suppose that the experimental results show the coin turning up heads 14 times out of 20 total flips.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The full data X would be a sequence of twenty times the symbol "H" or "T".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The statistic on which one might focus could be the total number T of heads.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The null hypothesis is that the coin is fair, and coin tosses are independent of one another.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] If a right-tailed test is considered, which would be the case if one is actually interested in the possibility that the coin is biased towards falling heads, then the *p*-value of this result is the chance of a fair coin landing on heads *at least* 14 times out of 20 flips.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] This probability is the *p*-value, considering only extreme results that favor heads.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] However, one might be interested in deviations in either direction, favoring either heads or tails.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The two-tailed *p*-value, which considers deviations favoring either heads or tails, may instead be calculated.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] As the binomial distribution is symmetrical for a fair coin, the two-sided *p*-value is simply twice the above calculated single-sided *p*-value: the two-sided *p*-value is 0.115.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The Pr(no. of heads ≤ 14 heads) = 1 − Pr(no. of heads ≥ 14 heads) + Pr(no. of head = 14) = 1 − 0.058 + 0.036 = 0.978; however, the symmetry of this binomial distribution makes it an unnecessary computation to find the smaller of the two probabilities.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Here, the calculated *p*-value exceeds 0.05, meaning that the data falls within the range of what would happen 95% of the time, if the coin were fair.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Hence, the null hypothesis is not rejected at the 0.05 level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] However, had one more head been obtained, the resulting *p*-value (two-tailed) would have been 0.0414 (4.14%), in which case the null hypothesis would be rejected at the 0.05 level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The difference between the two meanings of "extreme" appear when we consider a sequential hypothesis testing, or optional stopping, for the fairness of the coin.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In general, optional stopping changes how p-value is calculated.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] This experiment has 7 types of outcomes: 2 heads, 2 tails, 5 heads 1 tail, ..., 1 head 5 tails.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] We now calculate the *p*-value of the "3 heads 3 tails" outcome.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] If we use the test statistic # ${\text{heads}}/{\text{tails}}$ , then under the null hypothesis (i.e. # ${\text{heads}}\leq 3$ ) the two-sided *p*-value is exactly equal to 1, and both the one-sided left-tail p-value and the one-sided right-tail *p*-value are exactly equal to $19/32$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] However, suppose we have planned to simply flip the coin 6 times no matter what happens, then the second definition of *p*-value would mean that the *p*-value of "3 heads 3 tails" is exactly 1.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Thus, the "at least as extreme" definition of *p*-value is deeply contextual and depends on what the experimenter *planned* to do even in situations that did not occur.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-value was first formally introduced by Karl Pearson, in his Pearson's chi-squared test, using the chi-squared distribution and notated as capital P.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *p*-values for the chi-squared distribution (for various values of χ2 and degrees of freedom), now notated as *P,* were calculated in (Elderton 1902), collected in (Pearson 1914, pp. xxxi–xxxiii, 26–28, Table XII).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Ronald Fisher formalized and popularized the use of the *p*-value in statistics, with it playing a central role in his approach to the subject.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] That allowed computed values of χ2 to be compared against cutoffs and encouraged the use of *p*-values (especially 0.05, 0.02, and 0.01) as cutoffs, instead of computing and reporting *p*-values themselves.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The same type of tables were then compiled in (Fisher & Yates 1938), which cemented the approach.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] As an illustration of the application of *p*-values to the design and interpretation of experiments, in his following book *The Design of Experiments* (1935), Fisher presented the lady tasting tea experiment, which is the archetypal example of the *p*-value.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] He also applies this threshold to the design of experiments, noting that had only 6 cups been presented (3 of each), a perfect classification would have only yielded a *p*-value of $1/{\binom {6}{3}}=1/20=0.05,$ which would not have met this level of significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Fisher also underlined the interpretation of *p,* as the long-run proportion of values at least as extreme as the data, assuming the null hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In later editions, Fisher explicitly contrasted the use of the *p*-value for statistical inference in science with the Neyman–Pearson method, which he terms "Acceptance Procedures".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Fisher emphasizes that while fixed levels such as 5%, 2%, and 1% are convenient, the exact *p*-value can be used, and the strength of evidence can and will be revised with further experimentation.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] In contrast, decision procedures require a clear-cut decision, yielding an irreversible action, and the procedure is based on costs of error, which, he argues, are inapplicable to scientific research.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *E-value* can refer to two concepts, both of which are related to the p-value and both of which play a role in multiple testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] First, it corresponds to a generic, more robust alternative to the p-value that can deal with *optional continuation* of experiments.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Second, it is also used to abbreviate "expect value", which is the expected number of times that one expects to obtain a test statistic at least as extreme as the one that was actually observed if one assumes that the null hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] This expect-value is the product of the number of tests and the *p*-value.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The *q*-value is the analog of the *p*-value with respect to the positive false discovery rate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] It is used in multiple hypothesis testing to maintain statistical power while minimizing the false positive rate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The Probability of Direction (*pd*) is the Bayesian numerical equivalent of the *p*-value.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] It corresponds to the proportion of the posterior distribution that is of the median's sign, typically varying between 50% and 100%, and representing the certainty with which an effect is positive or negative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] Second-generation p-values extend the concept of p-values by not considering extremely small, practically irrelevant effect sizes as significant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The S-value, also known as the surprisal value, has been defined as a logarithmic transformation of the p-value: S-value = - log2(p-value).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/p-value] The transformation into S-values is intended to facilitate the interpretation of p-values by using a more intuitive logarithmic scale that indicates how “surprised” one is by a result.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] In statistics, the **score test** assesses constraints on statistical parameters based on the gradient of the likelihood function—known as the *score*—evaluated at the hypothesized parameter value under the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Intuitively, if the restricted estimator is near the maximum of the likelihood function, the score should not differ from zero by more than sampling error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] While the finite sample distributions of score tests are generally unknown, they have an asymptotic χ2-distribution under the null hypothesis as first proved by C.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Rao in 1948, a fact that can be used to determine statistical significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] The equivalence of these two approaches was first shown by S.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Silvey in 1959, which led to the name **Lagrange Multiplier (LM) test** that has become more commonly used, particularly in econometrics, since Breusch and Pagan's much-cited 1980 paper.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] The main advantage of the score test over the Wald test and likelihood-ratio test is that the score test only requires the computation of the restricted estimator.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] This makes testing feasible when the unconstrained maximum likelihood estimate is a boundary point in the parameter space.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Further, because the score test only requires the estimation of the likelihood function under the null hypothesis, it is less specific than the likelihood ratio test about the alternative hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Let L be the likelihood function which depends on a univariate parameter $\theta$ and let x be the data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] which has an asymptotic distribution of $\chi _{1}^{2}$ , when ${\mathcal {H}}_{0}$ is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] While asymptotically identical, calculating the LM statistic using the outer-gradient-product estimator of the Fisher information matrix can lead to bias in small samples.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Note that some texts use an alternative notation, in which the statistic $S^{*}(\theta )={\sqrt {S(\theta )}}$ is tested against a normal distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] This approach is equivalent and gives identical results.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] where L is the likelihood function, $\theta _{0}$ is the value of the parameter of interest under the null hypothesis, and C is a constant set depending on the size of the test desired (i.e. the probability of rejecting $H_{0}$ if $H_{0}$ is true; see Type I error).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] The score test is the most powerful test for small deviations from $H_{0}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] To see this, consider testing $\theta =\theta _{0}$ versus $\theta =\theta _{0}+h$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] and identifying the C above with $\log(K)$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] If the null hypothesis is true, the likelihood ratio test, the Wald test, and the score test are asymptotically equivalent tests of hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] When testing nested models, the statistics for each test then converge to a Chi-squared distribution with degrees of freedom equal to the difference in degrees of freedom in the two models.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] If the null hypothesis is not true, however, the statistics converge to a noncentral chi-squared distribution with possibly different noncentrality parameters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] A more general score test can be derived when there is more than one parameter.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] Suppose that ${\widehat {\theta }}_{0}$ is the maximum likelihood estimate of $\theta$ under the null hypothesis $H_{0}$ while U and I are respectively, the score vector and the Fisher information matrix.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] The actual formula for the test statistic depends on which estimator of the Fisher information matrix is being used.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] In many situations, the score statistic reduces to another commonly used statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] In linear regression, the Lagrange multiplier test can be expressed as a function of the *F*-test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] When the data follows a normal distribution, the score statistic is the same as the t statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/score-test] When the data consists of binary observations, the score statistic is the same as the chi-squared statistic in the Pearson's chi-squared test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A **statistical hypothesis test** is a method of statistical inference used to decide whether the data provide sufficient evidence to reject a particular hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A statistical hypothesis test typically involves a calculation of a test statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Then a decision is made, either by comparing the test statistic to a critical value or equivalently by evaluating a *p*-value computed from the test statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Roughly 100 specialized statistical tests are in use.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The goal of a hypothesis test is to establish whether certain properties of a statistical population are true by examining sample data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Typically, the population is modelled by a random variable whose distribution has unknown parameters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] For example, a medical trial may wish to establish whether a particular drug is effective in treating high blood pressure, with "the change in blood pressure observed in a patient who takes the drug" being the random variable.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] An example hypothesis could be "the mean change in blood pressure is zero" or "the mean change in blood pressure is negative".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In general, any statement about the parameters describing a **population** can be a hypothesis (but not a statement about the sample).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test compares two hypotheses: a default "null" hypothesis (denoted H0) and its negation, the "alternative" hypothesis (H1).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Typically the test will select a null hypothesis that the intervention being studied has no effect, or that the population parameter takes some "obvious" value.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A test statistic is computed from the given sample data, and the tester calculates the conditional probability of observing a value at least this extreme, supposing the null hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] If this probability (called the p-value) is less than the significance level of the test (denoted $\alpha$ ), then the null hypothesis is rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test does **not** conclude that the null hypothesis is false, or that the probability that the null hypothesis is false is less than $\alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Because it is usually impossible to definitely establish whether the hypothesis being tested is true or false from a sample, the conclusion of a hypothesis test is not certain to be correct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A statistical hypothesis test compares a test statistic (*z* or *t* for examples) to a threshold.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test statistic (the formula found in the table below) is based on optimality.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] For a fixed level of Type I error rate, use of these statistics minimizes Type II error rates (equivalent to maximizing power).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] While hypothesis testing was popularized early in the 20th century, early forms were used in the 1700s.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The first use is credited to John Arbuthnot (1710), followed by Pierre-Simon Laplace (1770s), in analyzing the human sex ratio at birth; see § Human sex ratio.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Ronald Fisher began his life in statistics as a Bayesian (Zabell 1992), but Fisher soon grew disenchanted with the subjectivity involved (namely use of the principle of indifference when determining prior probabilities), and sought to provide a more "objective" approach to inductive inference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher emphasized rigorous experimental design and methods to extract a result from few samples assuming Gaussian distributions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman (who teamed with the younger Pearson) emphasized mathematical rigor and methods to obtain more results from many samples and a wider range of distributions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Modern hypothesis testing is an inconsistent hybrid of the Fisher vs Neyman/Pearson formulation, methods and terminology developed in the early 20th century.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher popularized the "significance test".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] He required a null-hypothesis (corresponding to a population frequency distribution) and a sample.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] His (now familiar) calculations determined whether to reject the null-hypothesis or not.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Significance testing did not utilize an alternative hypothesis so there was no concept of a Type II error (false negative).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The *p*-value was devised as an informal, but objective, index meant to help a researcher determine (based on other knowledge) whether to modify future experiments or strengthen one's faith in the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing (and Type I/II errors) was devised by Neyman and Pearson as a more objective alternative to Fisher's *p*-value, also meant to determine researcher behaviour, but without requiring any inductive inference by the researcher.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman & Pearson considered a different problem to Fisher (which they called "hypothesis testing").
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] They initially considered two simple hypotheses (both with frequency distributions).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] They calculated two probabilities and typically selected the hypothesis associated with the higher probability (the hypothesis more likely to have generated the sample).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Their method always selected a hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] It also allowed the calculation of both types of error probabilities.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher and Neyman/Pearson clashed bitterly.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman/Pearson considered their formulation to be an improved generalization of significance testing (the defining paper was abstract; Mathematicians have generalized and refined the theory for decades).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher thought that it was not applicable to scientific research because often, during the course of the experiment, it is discovered that the initial assumptions about the null hypothesis are questionable due to unexpected sources of error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] He believed that the use of rigid reject/accept decisions based on models formulated before data is collected was incompatible with this common scenario faced by scientists and attempts to apply this method to scientific research would lead to mass confusion.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The dispute between Fisher and Neyman–Pearson was waged on philosophical grounds, characterized by a philosopher as a dispute over the proper role of models in statistical inference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman accepted a position in the University of California, Berkeley in 1938, breaking his partnership with Pearson and separating the disputants (who had previously occupied the same building).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The dispute between Fisher and Neyman terminated (unresolved after 27 years) with Fisher's death in 1962.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Some of Neyman's later publications reported *p*-values and significance levels.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The modern version of hypothesis testing is generally called the **null hypothesis significance testing (NHST)** and is a hybrid of the Fisher approach with the Neyman-Pearson approach.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Nickerson wrote an article stating that NHST was (at the time) "arguably the most widely used method of analysis of data collected in psychological experiments and has been so for about 70 years" and that it was at the same time "very controversial".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] This fusion resulted from confusion by writers of statistical textbooks (as predicted by Fisher) beginning in the 1940s (but signal detection, for example, still uses the Neyman/Pearson formulation).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Great conceptual differences and many caveats in addition to those mentioned above were ignored.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman and Pearson provided the stronger terminology, the more rigorous mathematics and the more consistent philosophy, but the subject taught today in introductory statistics has more similarities with Fisher's method than theirs.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Sometime around 1940, authors of statistical text books began combining the two approaches by using the *p*-value in place of the test statistic (or data) to test against the Neyman–Pearson "significance level".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Paul Meehl has argued that the epistemological importance of the choice of null hypothesis has gone largely unacknowledged.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the null hypothesis is predicted by theory, a more precise experiment will be a more severe test of the underlying theory.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the null hypothesis defaults to "no difference" or "no effect", a more precise experiment is a less severe test of the theory that motivated performing the experiment.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher and Neyman opposed the subjectivity of probability.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Their views contributed to the objective definitions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The core of their historical disagreement was philosophical.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Many of the philosophical criticisms of hypothesis testing are discussed by statisticians in other contexts, particularly correlation does not imply causation and the design of experiments.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing is of continuing interest to philosophers.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistics is increasingly being taught in schools with hypothesis testing being one of the elements taught.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Many conclusions reported in the popular press (political opinion polls to medical studies) are based on statistics.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] An introductory college statistics class places much emphasis on hypothesis testing – perhaps half of the course.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Such fields as literature and divinity now include findings based on statistical analysis (see the Bible Analyzer).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] An introductory statistics class teaches hypothesis testing as a cookbook process.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing is also taught at the postgraduate level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statisticians learn how to create good statistical test procedures (like *z*, Student's *t*, *F* and chi-squared).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistical hypothesis testing is considered a mature area within statistics, but a limited amount of development continues.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] An academic study states that the cookbook method of teaching introductory statistics leaves no time for history, philosophy or controversy.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing has been taught as received unified method.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Surveys showed that graduates of the class were filled with philosophical misconceptions (on all aspects of statistical inference) that persisted among instructors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] While the problem was addressed more than a decade ago, and calls for educational reform continue, students still graduate from statistics classes holding fundamental misconceptions about hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Ideas for improving the teaching of hypothesis testing include encouraging students to search for statistical errors in published papers, teaching the history of statistics and emphasizing the controversy in a generally dry subject.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Select a relevant statistical test with associated test statistic *T*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Derive the distribution of the test statistic under the null hypothesis from the assumptions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In standard cases this will be a well-known result.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] For example, the test statistic might follow a Student's t distribution with known degrees of freedom, or a normal distribution with known mean and variance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Select a significance level (*α*), the maximum acceptable false positive rate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Compute from the observations the observed value *t*obs of the test statistic *T*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Decide to either reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative or not reject it.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The Neyman-Pearson decision rule is to reject the null hypothesis *H*0 if the observed value *t*obs is in the critical region, and not to reject the null hypothesis otherwise.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The former report is adequate, the latter gives a more detailed explanation of the data and the reason why the suitcase is being checked.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Not rejecting the null hypothesis does not mean the null hypothesis is "accepted" per se (though Neyman and Pearson used that word in their original writings; see the Interpretation section).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The processes described here are perfectly adequate for computation.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] They seriously neglect the design of experiments considerations.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] It is particularly critical that appropriate sample sizes be estimated before conducting the experiment.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The phrase "test of significance" was coined by statistician Ronald Fisher.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the null hypothesis is true and statistical assumptions are met, the probability that the p-value will be less than or equal to the significance level $\alpha$ is at most $\alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] This ensures that the hypothesis test maintains its specified false positive rate (provided that statistical assumptions are met).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The *p*-value is the probability that a test statistic which is at least as extreme as the one obtained would occur under the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] At a significance level of 0.05, a fair coin would be expected to (incorrectly) reject the null hypothesis (that it is fair) in 1 out of 20 tests on average.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The *p*-value does not provide the probability that either the null hypothesis or its opposite is correct (a common source of confusion).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the *p*-value is less than the chosen significance threshold (equivalently, if the observed test statistic is in the critical region), then we say the null hypothesis is rejected at the chosen level of significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the *p*-value is *not* less than the chosen significance threshold (equivalently, if the observed test statistic is outside the critical region), then the null hypothesis is not rejected at the chosen level of significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the "lady tasting tea" example (below), Fisher required the lady to properly categorize all of the cups of tea to justify the conclusion that the result was unlikely to result from chance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] His test revealed that if the lady was effectively guessing at random (the null hypothesis), there was a 1.4% chance that the observed results (perfectly ordered tea) would occur.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistics are helpful in analyzing most collections of data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] This is equally true of hypothesis testing which can justify conclusions even when no scientific theory exists.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the Lady tasting tea example, it was "obvious" that no difference existed between (milk poured into tea) and (tea poured into milk).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistical hypothesis testing plays an important role in the whole of statistics and in statistical inference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Significance testing has been the favored statistical tool in some experimental social sciences (over 90% of articles in the *Journal of Applied Psychology* during the early 1990s).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Other fields have favored the estimation of parameters (e.g. effect size).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Significance testing is used as a substitute for the traditional comparison of predicted value and experimental result at the core of the scientific method.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] When theory is only capable of predicting the sign of a relationship, a directional (one-sided) hypothesis test can be configured so that only a statistically significant result supports theory.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] This form of theory appraisal is the most heavily criticized application of hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] "If the government required statistical procedures to carry warning labels like those on drugs, most inference methods would have long labels indeed." This caution applies to hypothesis tests and alternatives to them.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The successful hypothesis test is associated with a probability and a type-I error rate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The conclusion of the test is only as solid as the sample upon which it is based.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The design of the experiment is critical.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A statistical analysis of misleading data produces misleading conclusions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The issue of data quality can be more subtle.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In forecasting for example, there is no agreement on a measure of forecast accuracy.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the absence of a consensus measurement, no decision based on measurements will be without controversy.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Publication bias: Statistically nonsignificant results may be less likely to be published, which can bias the literature.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Multiple testing: When multiple true null hypothesis tests are conducted at once without adjustment, the overall probability of Type I error is higher than the nominal alpha level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Those making critical decisions based on the results of a hypothesis test are prudent to look at the details rather than the conclusion alone.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the physical sciences most results are fully accepted only when independently confirmed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Bootstrap-based resampling methods can be used for null hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A bootstrap creates numerous simulated samples by randomly resampling (with replacement) the original, combined sample data, assuming the null hypothesis is correct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The bootstrap is very versatile as it is distribution-free and it does not rely on restrictive parametric assumptions, but rather on empirical approximate methods with asymptotic guarantees.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Traditional parametric hypothesis tests are more computationally efficient but make stronger structural assumptions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In situations where computing the probability of the test statistic under the null hypothesis is hard or impossible (due to perhaps inconvenience or lack of knowledge of the underlying distribution), the bootstrap offers a viable method for statistical inference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The earliest use of statistical hypothesis testing is generally credited to the question of whether male and female births are equally likely (null hypothesis), which was addressed in the 1700s by John Arbuthnot (1710), and later by Pierre-Simon Laplace (1770s).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Arbuthnot examined birth records in London for each of the 82 years from 1629 to 1710, and applied the sign test, a simple non-parametric test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In every year, the number of males born in London exceeded the number of females.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Considering more male or more female births as equally likely, the probability of the observed outcome is 0.582, or about 1 in 4,836,000,000,000,000,000,000,000; in modern terms, this is the *p*-value.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Laplace considered the statistics of almost half a million births.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The statistics showed an excess of boys compared to girls.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] He concluded by calculation of a *p*-value that the excess was a real, but unexplained, effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In a famous example of hypothesis testing, known as the *Lady tasting tea*, Dr.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Muriel Bristol, a colleague of Fisher, claimed to be able to tell whether the tea or the milk was added first to a cup.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher proposed to give her eight cups, four of each variety, in random order.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] One could then ask what the probability was for her getting the number she got correct, but just by chance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The null hypothesis was that the Lady had no such ability.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test statistic was a simple count of the number of successes in selecting the four cups.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The critical region was the single case of 4 successes of 4 possible based on a conventional probability criterion (< 5%).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A pattern of 4 successes corresponds to 1 out of 70 possible combinations (p≈ 1.4%).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher asserted that no alternative hypothesis was (ever) required.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The lady correctly identified every cup, which would be considered a statistically significant result.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A person (the subject) is tested for clairvoyance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] They are shown the back face of a randomly chosen playing card 25 times and asked which of the four suits it belongs to.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The number of hits, or correct answers, is called *X*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] As we try to find evidence of their clairvoyance, for the time being the null hypothesis is that the person is not clairvoyant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The alternative is: the person is (more or less) clairvoyant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the null hypothesis is valid, the only thing the test person can do is guess.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] For every card, the probability (relative frequency) of any single suit appearing is 1/4.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the alternative is valid, the test subject will predict the suit correctly with probability greater than 1/4.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] We will call the probability of guessing correctly *p*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] When the test subject correctly predicts all 25 cards, we will consider them clairvoyant, and reject the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] With only 5 or 6 hits, on the other hand, there is no cause to consider them so.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] What is the critical number, *c*, of hits, at which point we consider the subject to be clairvoyant?
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] How do we determine the critical value *c*?
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] With the choice *c*=25 (i.e. we only accept clairvoyance when all cards are predicted correctly) we're more critical than with *c*=10.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the first case almost no test subjects will be recognized to be clairvoyant, in the second case, a certain number will pass the test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In practice, one decides how critical one will be.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] That is, one decides how often one accepts an error of the first kind – a false positive, or Type I error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The probability of a false positive is the probability of randomly guessing correctly all 25 times.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Thus, *c* = 10 yields a much greater probability of false positive.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Before the test is actually performed, the maximum acceptable probability of a Type I error (*α*) is determined.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Typically, values in the range of 1% to 5% are selected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] (If the maximum acceptable error rate is zero, an infinite number of correct guesses is required.) Depending on this Type 1 error rate, the critical value *c* is calculated.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] From all the numbers c, with this property, we choose the smallest, in order to minimize the probability of a Type II error, a false negative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] For the above example, we select: $c=13$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistical hypothesis testing is a key technique of both frequentist inference and Bayesian inference, although the two types of inference have notable differences.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statistical hypothesis tests define a procedure that controls (fixes) the probability of incorrectly *deciding* that a default position (null hypothesis) is incorrect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The procedure is based on how likely it would be for a set of observations to occur if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] This probability of making an incorrect decision is *not* the probability that the null hypothesis is true, nor whether any specific alternative hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] This contrasts with other possible techniques of decision theory in which the null and alternative hypothesis are treated on a more equal basis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] One naïve Bayesian approach to hypothesis testing is to base decisions on the posterior probability, but this fails when comparing point and continuous hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Other approaches to decision making, such as Bayesian decision theory, attempt to balance the consequences of incorrect decisions across all possibilities, rather than concentrating on a single null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A number of other approaches to reaching a decision based on data are available via decision theory and optimal decisions, some of which have desirable properties.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing, though, is a dominant approach to data analysis in many fields of science.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Extensions to the theory of hypothesis testing include the study of the power of tests, i.e. the probability of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis given that it is false.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Such considerations can be used for the purpose of sample size determination prior to the collection of data.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] An example of Neyman–Pearson hypothesis testing (or null hypothesis statistical significance testing) can be made by a change to the radioactive suitcase example.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] If the "suitcase" is actually a shielded container for the transportation of radioactive material, then a test might be used to select among three hypotheses: no radioactive source present, one present, two (all) present.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The test could be required for safety, with actions required in each case.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The Neyman–Pearson lemma of hypothesis testing says that a good criterion for the selection of hypotheses is the ratio of their probabilities (a likelihood ratio).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A simple method of solution is to select the hypothesis with the highest probability for the Geiger counts observed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The typical result matches intuition: few counts imply no source, many counts imply two sources and intermediate counts imply one source.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Notice also that usually there are problems for proving a negative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Null hypotheses should be at least falsifiable.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman–Pearson theory can accommodate both prior probabilities and the costs of actions resulting from decisions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The former allows each test to consider the results of earlier tests (unlike Fisher's significance tests).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The latter allows the consideration of economic issues (for example) as well as probabilities.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A likelihood ratio remains a good criterion for selecting among hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The two forms of hypothesis testing are based on different problem formulations.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The original test is analogous to a true/false question; the Neyman–Pearson test is more like multiple choice.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] In the view of Tukey the former produces a conclusion on the basis of only strong evidence while the latter produces a decision on the basis of available evidence.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] While the two tests seem quite different both mathematically and philosophically, later developments lead to the opposite claim.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The hypotheses become 0,1,2,3... grains of radioactive sand.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] There is little distinction between none or some radiation (Fisher) and 0 grains of radioactive sand versus all of the alternatives (Neyman–Pearson).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The major Neyman–Pearson paper of 1933 also considered composite hypotheses (ones whose distribution includes an unknown parameter).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] An example proved the optimality of the (Student's) *t*-test, "there can be no better test for the hypothesis under consideration" (p 321).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman–Pearson theory was proving the optimality of Fisherian methods from its inception.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher's significance testing has proven a popular flexible statistical tool in application with little mathematical growth potential.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neyman–Pearson hypothesis testing is claimed as a pillar of mathematical statistics, creating a new paradigm for the field.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] It also stimulated new applications in statistical process control, detection theory, decision theory and game theory.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Both formulations have been successful, but the successes have been of a different character.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The dispute over formulations is unresolved.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Science primarily uses Fisher's (slightly modified) formulation as taught in introductory statistics.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Statisticians study Neyman–Pearson theory in graduate school.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Mathematicians are proud of uniting the formulations.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Learned opinions deem the formulations variously competitive (Fisher vs Neyman), incompatible or complementary.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The dispute has become more complex since Bayesian inference has achieved respectability.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing can mean any mixture of two formulations that both changed with time.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Any discussion of significance testing vs hypothesis testing is doubly vulnerable to confusion.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher thought that hypothesis testing was a useful strategy for performing industrial quality control, however, he strongly disagreed that hypothesis testing could be useful for scientists.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Hypothesis testing provides a means of finding test statistics used in significance testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The concept of power is useful in explaining the consequences of adjusting the significance level and is heavily used in sample size determination.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The two methods remain philosophically distinct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] They usually (but *not always*) produce the same mathematical answer.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The preferred answer is context dependent.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] While the existing merger of Fisher and Neyman–Pearson theories has been heavily criticized, modifying the merger to achieve Bayesian goals has been considered.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Critics and supporters are largely in factual agreement regarding the characteristics of null hypothesis significance testing (NHST): While it can provide critical information, it is *inadequate as the sole tool for statistical analysis*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] *Successfully rejecting the null hypothesis may offer no support for the research hypothesis.* The continuing controversy concerns the selection of the best statistical practices for the near-term future given the existing practices.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] However, adequate research design can minimize this issue.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Critics would prefer to ban NHST completely, forcing a complete departure from those practices, while supporters suggest a less absolute change.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Controversy over significance testing, and its effects on publication bias in particular, has produced several results.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Textbooks have added some cautions, and increased coverage of the tools necessary to estimate the size of the sample required to produce significant results.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Few major organizations have abandoned use of significance tests although some have discussed doing so.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] A unifying position of critics is that statistics should not lead to an accept-reject conclusion or decision, but to an estimated value with an interval estimate; this data-analysis philosophy is broadly referred to as estimation statistics.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Estimation statistics can be accomplished with either frequentist or Bayesian methods.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Critics of significance testing have advocated basing inference less on p-values and more on confidence intervals for effect sizes for importance, prediction intervals for confidence, replications and extensions for replicability, meta-analyses for generality :.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] But none of these suggested alternatives inherently produces a decision.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Bayesian inference is one proposed alternative to significance testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] (Nickerson cited 10 sources suggesting it, including Rozeboom (1960)).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] For example, Bayesian parameter estimation can provide rich information about the data from which researchers can draw inferences, while using uncertain priors that exert only minimal influence on the results when enough data is available.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Kruschke has suggested Bayesian estimation as an alternative for the *t*-test and has also contrasted Bayesian estimation for assessing null values with Bayesian model comparison for hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Two competing models/hypotheses can be compared using Bayes factors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Bayesian methods could be criticized for requiring information that is seldom available in the cases where significance testing is most heavily used.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neither the prior probabilities nor the probability distribution of the test statistic under the alternative hypothesis are often available in the social sciences.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Advocates of a Bayesian approach sometimes claim that the goal of a researcher is most often to objectively assess the probability that a hypothesis is true based on the data they have collected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Neither Fisher's significance testing, nor Neyman–Pearson hypothesis testing can provide this information, and do not claim to.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] The probability a hypothesis is true can only be derived from use of Bayes' Theorem, which was unsatisfactory to both the Fisher and Neyman–Pearson camps due to the explicit use of subjectivity in the form of the prior probability.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-hypothesis-test] Fisher's strategy is to sidestep this with the *p*-value (an objective *index* based on the data alone) followed by *inductive inference*, while Neyman–Pearson devised their approach of *inductive behaviour*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In frequentist statistics, **power** is the probability of detecting an effect (i.e. rejecting the null hypothesis) given that some prespecified effect actually exists using a given test in a given context.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] More formally, in the case of a simple hypothesis test with two hypotheses, the **power of the test** is the probability that the test correctly rejects the null hypothesis ( $H_{0}$ ) when the alternative hypothesis ( $H_{1}$ ) is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] It is commonly denoted by $1-\beta$ , where $\beta$ is the probability of making a type II error (a false negative) conditional on there being a true effect or association.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Statistical testing uses data from samples to assess, or make inferences about, a statistical population.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For example, we may measure the yields of samples of two varieties of a crop, and use a two sample test to assess whether the mean values of this yield differs between varieties.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Under a frequentist hypothesis testing framework, this is done by calculating a test statistic (such as a t-statistic) for the dataset, which has a known theoretical probability distribution if there is no difference (the so-called null hypothesis).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If the actual value calculated on the sample is sufficiently unlikely to arise under the null hypothesis, we say we identified a statistically significant effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The threshold for significance can be set small to ensure there is little chance of falsely detecting a non-existent effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] However, failing to identify a significant effect does not imply there was none.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If we insist on being careful to avoid false positives, we may create false negatives instead.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] It may simply be too much to expect that we will be able to find satisfactorily strong evidence of a very subtle difference even if it exists.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Statistical power is an attempt to quantify this issue.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Suppose we are conducting a hypothesis test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] We define two hypotheses $H_{0}$ the null hypothesis, and $H_{1}$ the alternative hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If we design the test such that *α* is the significance level (*α* being the probability of rejecting $H_{0}$ when $H_{0}$ is in fact true) then the power of the test is 1 − *β* where *β* is the probability of failing to reject $H_{0}$ when the alternative $H_{1}$ is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] To make this more concrete, a typical statistical test would be based on a test statistic *t* calculated from the sampled data, which has a particular probability distribution under $H_{0}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] A desired significance level *α* would then define a corresponding "rejection region" (bounded by certain "critical values"), a set of values *t* is unlikely to take if $H_{0}$ was correct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If we reject $H_{0}$ in favor of $H_{1}$ only when the sample *t* takes those values, we would be able to keep the probability of falsely rejecting $H_{0}$ within our desired significance level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Statistical power is one minus the type II error probability and is also the sensitivity of the hypothesis testing procedure to detect a true effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] There is usually a trade-off between demanding more stringent tests (and so, smaller rejection regions) and trying to have a high probability of rejecting the null under the alternative hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Statistical power may also be extended to the case where multiple hypotheses are being tested based on an experiment or survey.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] It is thus also common to refer to the **power of a study**, evaluating a scientific project in terms of its ability to answer the research questions they are seeking to answer.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The main application of statistical power is "power analysis", a calculation of power usually done before an experiment is conducted using data from pilot studies or a literature review.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Power analyses can be used to calculate the minimum sample size required so that one can be reasonably likely to detect an effect of a given size (in other words, producing an acceptable level of power).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For example: "How many times do I need to toss a coin to conclude it is rigged by a certain amount?" If resources and thus sample sizes are fixed, power analyses can also be used to calculate the minimum effect size that is likely to be detected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Funding agencies, ethics boards and research review panels frequently request that a researcher perform a power analysis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] An underpowered study is likely be inconclusive, failing to allow one to choose between hypotheses at the desired significance level, while an overpowered study will spend great expense on being able to report significant effects even if they are tiny and so practically meaningless.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If a large number of underpowered studies are done and statistically significant results published, published findings are more likely false positives than true results, contributing to a replication crisis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] However, excessive demands for power could be connected to wasted resources and ethical problems, for example the use of a large number of animal test subjects when a smaller number would have been sufficient.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] It could also induce researchers trying to seek funding to overstate their expected effect sizes, or avoid looking for more subtle interaction effects that cannot be easily detected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Power analysis is primarily a frequentist statistics tool.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In Bayesian statistics, hypothesis testing of the type used in classical power analysis is not done.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In the Bayesian framework, one updates his or her prior beliefs using the data obtained in a given study.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In principle, a study that would be deemed underpowered from the perspective of hypothesis testing could still be used in such an updating process.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] However, power remains a useful measure of how much a given experiment size can be expected to refine one's beliefs.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] A study with low power is unlikely to lead to a large change in beliefs.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In addition, the concept of power is used to make comparisons between different statistical testing procedures: for example, between a parametric test and a nonparametric test of the same hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Tests may have the same size, and hence the same false positive rates, but different ability to detect true effects.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Consideration of their theoretical power proprieties is a key reason for the common use of likelihood ratio tests.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This expression can be rearranged, implying for example that 80% power is obtained when looking for a difference in means that exceeds about 4 times the group-wise standard error of the mean.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For a one sample t-test 16 is to be replaced with 8.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Other values provide an appropriate approximation when the desired power or significance level are different.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] However, a full power analysis should always be performed to confirm and refine this estimate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Statistical power may depend on a number of factors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For a given test, the **significance criterion** determines the desired degree of rigor, specifying how unlikely it is for the null hypothesis of no effect to be rejected if it is in fact true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The most commonly used threshold is a probability of rejection of 0.05, though smaller values like 0.01 or 0.001 are sometimes used.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This threshold then implies that the observation must be at least that unlikely (perhaps by suggesting a sufficiently large estimate of difference) to be considered strong enough evidence against the null.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Picking a smaller value to tighten the threshold, so as to reduce the chance of a false positive, would also reduce power (and so increase the chance of a false negative).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Some statistical tests will inherently produce better power, albeit often at the cost of requiring stronger assumptions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The **magnitude of the effect** of interest defines what is being looked for by the test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] It can be the expected effect size if it exists, as a scientific hypothesis that the researcher has arrived at and wishes to test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Alternatively, in a more practical context it could be determined by the size the effect must be to be useful, for example that which is required to be clinically significant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] An effect size can be a direct value of the quantity of interest (for example, a difference in mean of a particular size), or it can be a standardized measure that also accounts for the variability in the population (such as a difference in means expressed as a multiple of the standard deviation).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If the researcher is looking for a larger effect, then it should be easier to find with a given experimental or analytic setup, and so power is higher.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The nature of the **sample** underlies the information being used in the test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This will usually involve the sample size, and the sample variability, if that is not implicit in the definition of the effect size.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] More broadly, the precision with which the data are measured can also be an important factor (such as the statistical reliability), as well as the design of an experiment or observational study.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Ultimately, these factors lead to an expected amount of sampling error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] How increased sample size translates to higher power is a measure of the efficiency of the test—for example, the sample size required for a given power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The statistical power of a hypothesis test has an impact on the interpretation of its results.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Not finding a result with a more powerful study is stronger evidence against the effect existing than the same finding with a less powerful study.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] However, this is not completely conclusive.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The effect may exist, but be smaller than what was looked for, meaning the study is in fact underpowered and the sample is thus unable to distinguish it from random chance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Many clinical trials, for instance, have low statistical power to detect differences in adverse effects of treatments, since such effects may only affect a few patients, even if this difference can be important.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Conclusions about the probability of actual presence of an effect also should consider more things than a single test, especially as real world power is rarely close to 1.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Indeed, although there are no formal standards for power, many researchers and funding bodies assess power using 0.80 (or 80%) as a standard for adequacy.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This convention implies a four-to-one trade off between β-risk and α-risk, as the probability of a type II error β is set as 1 - 0.8 = 0.2, while α, the probability of a type I error, is commonly set at 0.05.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Some applications require much higher levels of power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Medical tests may be designed to minimise the number of false negatives (type II errors) produced by loosening the threshold of significance, raising the risk of obtaining a false positive (a type I error).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Power analysis focuses on the correct rejection of a null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Alternative concerns may however motivate an experiment, and so lead to different needs for sample size.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In many contexts, the issue is less about deciding between hypotheses but rather with getting an estimate of the population effect size of sufficient accuracy.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For example, a careful power analysis can tell you that 55 pairs of normally distributed samples with a correlation of 0.5 will be sufficient to grant 80% power in rejecting a null that the correlation is no more than 0.2 (using a one-sided test, α = 0.05).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] But the typical 95% confidence interval with this sample would be around [0.27, 0.67].
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] An alternative, albeit related analysis would be required if we wish to be able to measure correlation to an accuracy of ± 0.1, implying a different (in this case, larger) sample size.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Alternatively, multiple under-powered studies can still be useful, if appropriately combined through a meta-analysis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Many statistical analyses involve the estimation of several unknown quantities.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In simple cases, all but one of these quantities are nuisance parameters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In this setting, the only relevant power pertains to the single quantity that will undergo formal statistical inference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In some settings, particularly if the goals are more "exploratory", there may be a number of quantities of interest in the analysis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For example, in a multiple regression analysis we may include several covariates of potential interest.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In situations such as this where several hypotheses are under consideration, it is common that the powers associated with the different hypotheses differ.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For instance, in multiple regression analysis, the power for detecting an effect of a given size is related to the variance of the covariate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Since different covariates will have different variances, their powers will differ as well.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Additional complications arise when we consider these multiple hypotheses together.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For example, if we consider a false positive to be making an erroneous null rejection on any one of these hypotheses, our likelihood of this "family-wise error" will be inflated if appropriate measures are not taken.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Such measures typically involve applying a higher threshold of stringency to reject a hypothesis (such as with the Bonferroni method), and so would reduce power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Alternatively, there may be different notions of power connected with how the different hypotheses are considered.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] "Complete power" demands that all true effects are detected across all of the hypotheses, which is a much stronger requirement than the "minimal power" of being able to find at least one true effect, a type of power that might increase with an increasing number of hypotheses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Power analysis can either be done before (*a priori* or prospective power analysis) or after (*post hoc* or retrospective power analysis) data are collected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] *A priori* power analysis is conducted prior to the research study, and is typically used in estimating sufficient sample sizes to achieve adequate power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] *Post-hoc* analysis of "observed power" is conducted after a study has been completed, and uses the obtained sample size and effect size to determine what the power was in the study, assuming the effect size in the sample is equal to the effect size in the population.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Whereas the utility of prospective power analysis in experimental design is universally accepted, post hoc power analysis is controversial.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Many statisticians have argued that post-hoc power calculations are misleading and essentially meaningless.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] We are interested in being able to detect a positive change of size $\theta >0$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] We first set up the problem according to our test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Let $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ denote the pre-treatment and post-treatment measures on subject i , respectively.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The possible effect of the treatment should be visible in the differences $D_{i}=B_{i}-A_{i},$ which are assumed to be independent and identically Normal in distribution, with unknown mean value $\mu _{D}$ and variance $\sigma _{D}^{2}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] and ${\hat {\sigma }}_{D}$ is the sample standard deviation of the difference.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] We can proceed according to our knowledge of statistical theory, though in practice for a standard case like this software will exist to compute more accurate answers.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Thanks to t-test theory, we know this test statistic under the null hypothesis follows a Student t-distribution with $n-1$ degrees of freedom.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] If we wish to reject the null at significance level $\alpha =0.05\,$ , we must find the critical value $t_{\alpha }$ such that the probability of $T_{n}>t_{\alpha }$ under the null is equal to $\alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Now suppose that the alternative hypothesis $H_{1}$ is true so $\mu _{D}=\theta$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Then, writing the power as a function of the effect size, $B(\theta )$ , we find the probability of $T_{n}$ being above $t_{\alpha }$ under $H_{1}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] ${\frac {{\bar {D}}_{n}-\theta }{{\hat {\sigma }}_{D}/{\sqrt {n}}}}$ again follows a student-t distribution under $H_{1}$ , converging on to a standard normal distribution for large n.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] According to this formula, the power increases with the values of the effect size $\theta$ and the sample size n, and reduces with increasing variability $\sigma _{D}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In the trivial case of zero effect size, power is at a minimum (infimum) and equal to the significance level of the test $\alpha \,,$ in this example 0.05.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For finite sample sizes and non-zero variability, it is the case here, as is typical, that power cannot be made equal to 1 except in the trivial case where $\alpha =1$ so the null is *always* rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Alternatively we can use a Monte Carlo simulation method that works more generally.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Once again, we return to the assumption of the distribution of $D_{n}$ and the definition of $T_{n}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Suppose we have fixed values of the sample size, variability and effect size, and wish to compute power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Compute the resulting test statistic $T_{n}$ for each set.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Compute the $(1-\alpha )$ th quantile of the simulated $T_{n}$ and use that as an estimate of $t_{\alpha }$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Now generate a large number of sets of $D_{n}$ according to the alternative hypothesis, $N(\theta ,\sigma _{D})$ , and compute the corresponding test statistics again.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Look at the proportion of these simulated alternative $T_{n}$ that are above the $t_{\alpha }$ calculated in step 3 and so are rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This can be done with a variety of software packages.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Using this methodology with the values before, setting the sample size to 25 leads to an estimated power of around 0.78.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The small discrepancy with the previous section is due mainly to inaccuracies with the normal approximation.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Several studies have attempted to estimate typical levels of statistical power across different academic fields.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] One common approach uses meta-analyses to assess whether individual studies have sufficient power to detect the average effect size estimated from the meta-analysis itself.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This method essentially asks: how likely is each study to detect the consensus effect found in the broader literature?
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] These assessments consistently find low levels of statistical power across many disciplines.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] For example, using this method median power is 18% in economics, 10% in political science, 36% in psychology, and 15% in ecology and evolutionary biology.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] In the frequentist setting, parameters are assumed to have a specific value which is unlikely to be true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] This issue can be addressed by assuming the parameter has a distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The resulting power is sometimes referred to as Bayesian power which is commonly used in clinical trial design.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Both frequentist power and Bayesian power use statistical significance as the success criterion.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] However, statistical significance is often not enough to define success.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] To address this issue, the power concept can be extended to the concept of predictive probability of success (PPOS).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] The success criterion for PPOS is not restricted to statistical significance and is commonly used in clinical trial designs.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-power] Numerous free and/or open source programs are available for performing power and sample size calculations.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In statistical hypothesis testing, a result has **statistical significance** when a result at least as extreme would be very infrequent if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The result is said to be **statistically significant**, by the standards of the study, when $p\leq \alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The significance level for a study is chosen before data collection, and is typically set to 5% or much lower—depending on the field of study.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In any experiment or observation that involves drawing a sample from a population, there is always the possibility that an observed effect would have occurred due to sampling error alone.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] But if the *p*-value of an observed effect is less than (or equal to) the significance level, an investigator may conclude that the effect reflects the characteristics of the whole population, thereby rejecting the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] This technique for testing the statistical significance of results was developed in the early 20th century.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The term *significance* does not imply importance here, and the term *statistical significance* is not the same as research significance, theoretical significance, or practical significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] For example, the term clinical significance refers to the practical importance of a treatment effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Statistical significance dates to the 18th century, in the work of John Arbuthnot and Pierre-Simon Laplace, who computed the *p*-value for the human sex ratio at birth, assuming a null hypothesis of equal probability of male and female births; see *p*-value § History for details.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In 1925, Ronald Fisher advanced the idea of statistical hypothesis testing, which he called "tests of significance", in his publication *Statistical Methods for Research Workers*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Fisher suggested a probability of one in twenty (0.05) as a convenient cutoff level to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In a 1933 paper, Jerzy Neyman and Egon Pearson called this cutoff the *significance level*, which they named $\alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] They recommended that $\alpha$ be set ahead of time, prior to any data collection.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Despite his initial suggestion of 0.05 as a significance level, Fisher did not intend this cutoff value to be fixed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In his 1956 publication *Statistical Methods and Scientific Inference,* he recommended that significance levels be set according to specific circumstances.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The significance level $\alpha$ is the threshold for p below which the null hypothesis is rejected even though by assumption it were true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] This means that if indeed the null hypothesis is true, $\alpha$ is also the probability of mistakenly rejecting it anyway.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] This is also called false positive and type I error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Sometimes researchers talk about the confidence level *γ* = (1 − *α*) instead.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] This is the probability of not rejecting the null hypothesis given that it is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Confidence levels and confidence intervals were introduced by Neyman in 1937.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Statistical significance plays a pivotal role in statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] It is used to determine whether the null hypothesis should be rejected or retained.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The null hypothesis is the hypothesis that no effect exists in the phenomenon being studied.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] For the null hypothesis to be rejected, an observed result has to be statistically significant, i.e. the observed *p*-value is less than the pre-specified significance level $\alpha$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] To determine whether a result is statistically significant, a researcher calculates a *p*-value, which is the probability of observing an effect of the same magnitude or more extreme given that the null hypothesis is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The null hypothesis is rejected if the *p*-value is less than (or equal to) a predetermined level, $\alpha$ . $\alpha$ is also called the *significance level*, and is the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis given that it is true (a type I error).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] For example, when $\alpha$ is set to 5%, the conditional probability of a type I error, *given that the null hypothesis is true*, is 5%, and a statistically significant result is one where the observed *p*-value is less than (or equal to) 5%.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] When drawing data from a sample, this means that the rejection region comprises 5% of the sampling distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] These 5% can be allocated to one side of the sampling distribution, as in a one-tailed test, or partitioned to both sides of the distribution, as in a two-tailed test, with each tail (or rejection region) containing 2.5% of the distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The use of a one-tailed test is dependent on whether the research question or alternative hypothesis specifies a direction such as whether a group of objects is *heavier* or the performance of students on an assessment is *better*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] A two-tailed test may still be used but it will be less powerful than a one-tailed test, because the rejection region for a one-tailed test is concentrated on one end of the null distribution and is twice the size (5% vs.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] 2.5%) of each rejection region for a two-tailed test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] As a result, the null hypothesis can be rejected with a less extreme result if a one-tailed test was used.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The one-tailed test is only more powerful than a two-tailed test if the specified direction of the alternative hypothesis is correct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] If it is wrong, however, then the one-tailed test has no power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In specific fields such as particle physics and manufacturing, statistical significance is often expressed in multiples of the standard deviation or sigma (*σ*) of a normal distribution, with significance thresholds set at a much stricter level (for example 5*σ*).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] For instance, the certainty of the Higgs boson particle's existence was based on the 5*σ* criterion, which corresponds to a *p*-value of about 1 in 3.5 million.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In other fields of scientific research such as genome-wide association studies, significance levels as low as 5×10−8 are not uncommon—as the number of tests performed is extremely large.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Researchers focusing solely on whether their results are statistically significant might report findings that are not substantive and not replicable.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] There is also a difference between statistical significance and practical significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] A study that is found to be statistically significant may not necessarily be practically significant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Effect size is a measure of a study's practical significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] A statistically significant result may have a weak effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] To gauge the research significance of their result, researchers are encouraged to always report an effect size along with *p*-values.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] An effect size measure quantifies the strength of an effect, such as the distance between two means in units of standard deviation (cf.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Cohen's d), the correlation coefficient between two variables or its square, and other measures.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] A statistically significant result may not be easy to reproduce.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In particular, some statistically significant results will in fact be false positives.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Each failed attempt to reproduce a result increases the likelihood that the result was a false positive.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Starting in the 2010s, some journals began questioning whether significance testing, and particularly using a threshold of *α*=5%, was being relied on too heavily as the primary measure of validity of a hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Some journals encouraged authors to do more detailed analysis than just a statistical significance test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In social psychology, the journal *Basic and Applied Social Psychology* banned the use of significance testing altogether from papers it published, requiring authors to use other measures to evaluate hypotheses and impact.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Other editors, commenting on this ban have noted: "Banning the reporting of *p*-values, as Basic and Applied Social Psychology recently did, is not going to solve the problem because it is merely treating a symptom of the problem.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] There is nothing wrong with hypothesis testing and *p*-values per se as long as authors, reviewers, and action editors use them correctly." Some statisticians prefer to use alternative measures of evidence, such as likelihood ratios or Bayes factors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Using Bayesian statistics can avoid confidence levels, but also requires making additional assumptions, and may not necessarily improve practice regarding statistical testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] The widespread abuse of statistical significance represents an important topic of research in metascience.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] In 2017, a group of 72 authors proposed to enhance reproducibility by changing the *p*-value threshold for statistical significance from 0.05 to 0.005.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/statistical-significance] Additionally, the change to 0.005 would increase the likelihood of false negatives, whereby the effect being studied is real, but the test fails to show it.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] An analysis commits a Type I error when some baseline assumption is incorrectly rejected because of new, misleading information.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Meanwhile, a Type II error is made when such an assumption is maintained, due to flawed or insufficient data, when better measurements would have shown it to be untrue.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The manner in which a null hypothesis frames contextually default expectations influences the specific ways in which type I errors and type II errors manifest, and this varies by context and application.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Generally the risk of such errors cannot be entirely eliminated, only traded-off between the two types, by for example changing the significance threshold.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Knowledge of type I errors and type II errors is applied widely in fields of medical science, biometrics and computer science.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Minimising these errors is an object of study within statistical theory, though complete elimination of either is impossible when relevant outcomes are not determined by known, observable, causal processes.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In statistical test theory, the notion of a statistical error is an integral part of hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The test goes about choosing about two competing propositions called null hypothesis, denoted by ${\textstyle H_{0}}$ and alternative hypothesis, denoted by ${\textstyle H_{1}}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This is conceptually similar to the judgement in a court trial.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The null hypothesis corresponds to the position of the defendant: just as he is presumed to be innocent until proven guilty, so is the null hypothesis presumed to be true until the data provide convincing evidence against it.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The alternative hypothesis corresponds to the position against the defendant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Specifically, the null hypothesis also involves the absence of a difference or the absence of an association.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Thus, the null hypothesis can never be that there is a difference or an association.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] If the result of the test corresponds with reality, then a correct decision has been made.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] However, if the result of the test does not correspond with reality, then an error has occurred.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] There are two situations in which the decision is wrong.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The null hypothesis may be true, whereas we reject ${\textstyle H_{0}}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] On the other hand, the alternative hypothesis ${\textstyle H_{1}}$ may be true, whereas we do not reject ${\textstyle H_{0}}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Two types of error are distinguished: type I error and type II error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The first kind of error is the mistaken rejection of a null hypothesis as the result of a test procedure.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This kind of error is called a type I error (false positive) and is sometimes called an error of the first kind.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In terms of the courtroom example, a type I error corresponds to convicting an innocent defendant.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The second kind of error is the failure to reject the null hypothesis as the result of a test procedure.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This sort of error is called a type II error (false negative) and is also referred to as an error of the second kind.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In terms of the courtroom example, a type II error corresponds to acquitting a criminal.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The crossover error rate (CER) is the point at which type I errors and type II errors are equal.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A system with a lower CER value provides more accuracy than a system with a higher CER value.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] With all else being equal, having the rate of type I errors and type II errors being equal (i.e. the CER) will result in the lowest overall error rate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In terms of false positives and false negatives, a positive result corresponds to rejecting the null hypothesis, while a negative result corresponds to failing to reject the null hypothesis; "false" means the conclusion drawn is incorrect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Thus, a type I error is equivalent to a false positive, and a type II error is equivalent to a false negative.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A perfect test would have zero false positives and zero false negatives.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] However, statistical methods are probabilistic, and it cannot be known for certain whether statistical conclusions are correct.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Whenever there is uncertainty, there is the possibility of making an error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Considering this, all statistical hypothesis tests have a probability of making type I and type II errors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] These two types of error rates are traded off against each other: for any given sample set, the effort to reduce one type of error generally results in increasing the other type of error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The same idea can be expressed in terms of the rate of correct results and therefore used to minimize error rates and improve the quality of hypothesis test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] To reduce the probability of committing a type I error, making the alpha value more stringent is both simple and efficient.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] For example, setting the alpha value at 0.01, instead of 0.05.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] To decrease the probability of committing a type II error, which is closely associated with analyses' power, either increasing the test's sample size or relaxing the alpha level, ex. setting the alpha level to 0.1 instead of 0.05, could increase the analyses' power.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A test statistic is robust if the type I error rate is controlled.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Varying different threshold (cut-off) values could also be used to make the test either more specific or more sensitive, which in turn elevates the test quality.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] For example, imagine a medical test, in which an experimenter might measure the concentration of a certain protein in the blood sample.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The experimenter could adjust the threshold (black vertical line in the figure) and people would be diagnosed as having diseases if any number is detected above this certain threshold.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] According to the image, changing the threshold would result in changes in false positives and false negatives, corresponding to movement on the curve.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Since in a real experiment it is impossible to avoid all type I and type II errors, it is important to consider the amount of risk one is willing to take to falsely reject H0 or accept H0.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The solution to this question would be to report the p-value or significance level α of the statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] For example, if the p-value of a test statistic result is 0.0596, then there is a probability of 5.96% that we falsely reject H0 given it is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Or, if we say, the statistic is performed at level α, like 0.05, then we allow to falsely reject H0 at 5%.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A significance level α of 0.05 is relatively common, but there is no general rule that fits all scenarios.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The speed limit of a freeway in the United States is 120 kilometers per hour (75 mph).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A device is set to measure the speed of passing vehicles.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Suppose that the device will conduct three measurements of the speed of a passing vehicle, recording as a random sample X1, X2, X3.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The traffic police will or will not fine the drivers depending on the average speed ${\bar {X}}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In addition, we suppose that the measurements X1, X2, X3 are modeled as normal distribution N(μ,2).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Then, T should follow N(μ,2/ ${\sqrt {3}}$ ) and the parameter μ represents the true speed of passing vehicle.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] According to change-of-units rule for the normal distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] That is to say, if the recorded speed of a vehicle is greater than critical value 121.9, the driver will be fined.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] However, there are still 5% of the drivers are falsely fined since the recorded average speed is greater than 121.9 but the true speed does not pass 120, which we say, a type I error.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The type II error corresponds to the case that the true speed of a vehicle is over 120 kilometers per hour but the driver is not fined.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] which means, if the true speed of a vehicle is 125, the driver has the probability of 0.36% to avoid the fine when the statistic is performed at level α=0.05, since the recorded average speed is lower than 121.9.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] If the true speed is closer to 121.9 than 125, then the probability of avoiding the fine will also be higher.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The tradeoffs between type I error and type II error should also be considered.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] That is, in this case, if the traffic police do not want to falsely fine innocent drivers, the level α can be set to a smaller value, like 0.01.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] However, if that is the case, more drivers whose true speed is over 120 kilometers per hour, like 125, would be more likely to avoid the fine.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The terms "type I error" and "type II error" originate from a 1933 paper by Neyman and Pearson.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] It is standard practice for statisticians to conduct tests in order to determine whether or not a "speculative hypothesis" concerning the observed phenomena of the world (or its inhabitants) can be supported.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The results of such testing determine whether a particular set of results agrees reasonably (or does not agree) with the speculated hypothesis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This is why the hypothesis under test is often called the null hypothesis (most likely, coined by Fisher (1935, p.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] 19)), because it is *this* hypothesis that is to be either nullified or not nullified by the test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] When the null hypothesis is nullified, it is possible to conclude that data support the "alternative hypothesis" (which is the original speculated one).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] If the probability of obtaining a result as extreme as the one obtained, supposing that the null hypothesis were true, is lower than a pre-specified cut-off probability (for example, 5%), then the result is said to be statistically significant and the null hypothesis is rejected.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] To address issues with null hypothesis testing, Andrew Gelman, John Carlin and others have suggested Type S and Type M errors to add to consideration of significant results.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The Type S error rate corresponds to the probability that if a significant result is obtained, the effect is estimated in the wrong direction of the true effect.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This can occur often with low powered testing setups.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This is addressed through an "exaggeration factor", an assessment of the expected ratio of the absolute values of the estimate to the true value, conditional on a significant result being obtained.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This is important because using a significance test to screen results in selection bias, which can lead to drastically overestimating effect sizes.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In the practice of medicine, the differences between the applications of screening and testing are considerable.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Screening involves relatively cheap tests that are given to large populations, none of whom manifest any clinical indication of disease (e.g., Pap smears).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Testing involves far more expensive, often invasive, procedures that are given only to those who manifest some clinical indication of disease, and are most often applied to confirm a suspected diagnosis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] For example, most states in the US require newborns to be screened for phenylketonuria and hypothyroidism, among other congenital disorders.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Although they display a high rate of false positives, the screening tests are considered valuable because they greatly increase the likelihood of detecting these disorders at a far earlier stage.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The simple blood tests used to screen possible blood donors for HIV and hepatitis have a significant rate of false positives; however, physicians use much more expensive and far more precise tests to determine whether a person is actually infected with either of these viruses.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Perhaps the most widely discussed false positives in medical screening come from the breast cancer screening procedure mammography.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The US rate of false positive mammograms is up to 15%, the highest in world.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] One consequence of the high false positive rate in the US is that, in any 10-year period, half of the American women screened receive a false positive mammogram.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] False positive mammograms are costly, with over $100 million spent annually in the U.S. on follow-up testing and treatment.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] As a result of the high false positive rate in the US, as many as 90–95% of women who get a positive mammogram do not have the condition.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The lowest rate in the world is in the Netherlands, 1%.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The lowest rates are generally in Northern Europe where mammography films are read twice and a high threshold for additional testing is set (the high threshold decreases the power of the test).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The ideal population screening test would be cheap, easy to administer, and produce zero false negatives, if possible.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Such tests usually produce more false positives, which can subsequently be sorted out by more sophisticated (and expensive) testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] False negatives and false positives are significant issues in medical testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] False positives can also produce serious and counter-intuitive problems when the condition being searched for is rare, as in screening.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] If a test has a false positive rate of one in ten thousand, but only one in a million samples (or people) is a true positive, most of the positives detected by that test will be false.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The probability that an observed positive result is a false positive may be calculated using Bayes' theorem.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] False negatives produce serious and counter-intuitive problems, especially when the condition being searched for is common.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] If a test with a false negative rate of only 10% is used to test a population with a true occurrence rate of 70%, many of the negatives detected by the test will be false.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] This sometimes leads to inappropriate or inadequate treatment of both the patient and their disease.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A common example is relying on cardiac stress tests to detect coronary atherosclerosis, even though cardiac stress tests are known to only detect limitations of coronary artery blood flow due to advanced stenosis.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Biometric matching, such as for fingerprint recognition, facial recognition or iris recognition, is susceptible to type I and type II errors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The probability of type I errors is called the "false reject rate" (FRR) or false non-match rate (FNMR), while the probability of type II errors is called the "false accept rate" (FAR) or false match rate (FMR).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] If the system is designed to rarely match suspects then the probability of type II errors can be called the "false alarm rate".
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] On the other hand, if the system is used for validation (and acceptance is the norm) then the FAR is a measure of system security, while the FRR measures user inconvenience level.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In criminal legal proceedings, there is enormous emphasis on ensuring that if any error is committed it will be Type II error (letting an otherwise-culpable criminal defendant go free) rather than type I error (punishing an innocent person for a crime he or she did not commit).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] English jurist William Blackstone invented Blackstone's ratio of 10:1 to describe the concept that a fair system might let ten guilty defendants walk free rather than let more than one innocent person be jailed.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] In recent years, legal scholarship and mainstream jurisprudence has adopted the Type I and Type II error taxonomy to have a more rigorous vocabulary with which to discuss judicial mistakes and wrongful convictions.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Type II taxonomy in its discussion of errors in *Ballew v.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Georgia* and judges and law professors increasingly use this dichotomous designation rather than the more casual "wrongly convicted" or "erroneously acquitted," which were terms used often in earlier scholarship.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Recent scholarship and judicial concern often centers on the size and unanimity of juries as safeguards against Type I error (incorrectly convicting the innocent defendant).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Small juries of less than twelve have been criticized by the U.S.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] As to unanimity, on April 20, 2020, the U.S.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] Supreme Court ruled the Sixth Amendment requires a unanimous jury verdict to convict a defendant of a serious offense, citing concern around Type I error as among the primary reasons for requiring unanimous verdicts in serious criminal matters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] False positives are routinely found every day in airport security screening, which are ultimately visual inspection systems.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The installed security alarms are intended to prevent weapons being brought onto aircraft; yet they are often set to such high sensitivity that they alarm many times a day for minor items, such as keys, belt buckles, loose change, mobile phones, and tacks in shoes.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The ratio of false positives (identifying an innocent traveler as a terrorist) to true positives (detecting a would-be terrorist) is, therefore, very high; and because almost every alarm is a false positive, the positive predictive value of these screening tests is very low.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The relative cost of false results determines the likelihood that test creators allow these events to occur.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] The notions of false positives and false negatives have a wide currency in the realm of computers and computer applications, including computer security, spam filtering, malware, optical character recognition, and many others.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] While most anti-spam tactics can block or filter a high percentage of unwanted emails, doing so without creating significant false-positive results is a much more demanding task.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/type-i-and-type-ii-errors] A low number of false negatives is an indicator of the efficiency of spam filtering.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] In statistics, the **Wald test** (named after Abraham Wald) assesses constraints on statistical parameters based on the weighted distance between the unrestricted estimate and its hypothesized value under the null hypothesis, where the weight is the precision of the estimate.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] Intuitively, the larger this weighted distance, the less likely it is that the constraint is true.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] While the finite sample distributions of Wald tests are generally unknown, it has an asymptotic χ2-distribution under the null hypothesis, a fact that can be used to determine statistical significance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] Together with the Lagrange multiplier test and the likelihood-ratio test, the Wald test is one of three classical approaches to hypothesis testing.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] An advantage of the Wald test over the other two is that it only requires the estimation of the unrestricted model, which lowers the computational burden as compared to the likelihood-ratio test.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] However, a major disadvantage is that (in finite samples) it is not invariant to changes in the representation of the null hypothesis; in other words, algebraically equivalent expressions of non-linear parameter restriction can lead to different values of the test statistic.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] That is because the Wald statistic is derived from a Taylor expansion, and different ways of writing equivalent nonlinear expressions lead to nontrivial differences in the corresponding Taylor coefficients.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] Under the Wald test, the estimated ${\hat {\theta }}$ that was found as the maximizing argument of the unconstrained likelihood function is compared with a hypothesized value $\theta _{0}$ .
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] In particular, the squared difference ${\hat {\theta }}-\theta _{0}$ is weighted by the curvature of the log-likelihood function.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] which under the null hypothesis follows an asymptotic χ2-distribution with one degree of freedom.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] The square root of the single-restriction Wald statistic can be understood as a (pseudo) *t*-ratio that is, however, not actually *t*-distributed except for the special case of linear regression with normally distributed errors.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] In general, it follows an asymptotic *z* distribution.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] where $\operatorname {se} ({\widehat {\theta }})$ is the standard error (SE) of the maximum likelihood estimate (MLE), the square root of the variance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] There are several ways to consistently estimate the variance matrix which in finite samples leads to alternative estimates of standard errors and associated test statistics and *p*-values.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] The validity of still getting an asymptotically normal distribution after plugging in the MLE estimator of ${\hat {\theta }}$ into the SE relies on Slutsky's theorem.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] The Wald test can be used to test a single hypothesis on multiple parameters, as well as to test jointly multiple hypotheses on single/multiple parameters.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] where ${\hat {V}}_{n}$ is an estimator of the covariance matrix.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] What if the covariance matrix is not known a-priori and needs to be estimated from the data?
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] In the standard form, the Wald test is used to test linear hypotheses that can be represented by a single matrix *R*.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] where $c'({\hat {\theta }}_{n})$ is the derivative of c evaluated at the sample estimator.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] This result is obtained using the delta method, which uses a first order approximation of the variance.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] The fact that one uses an approximation of the variance has the drawback that the Wald statistic is not-invariant to a non-linear transformation/reparametrisation of the hypothesis: it can give different answers to the same question, depending on how the question is phrased.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] For example, asking whether *R* = 1 is the same as asking whether log *R* = 0; but the Wald statistic for *R* = 1 is not the same as the Wald statistic for log *R* = 0 (because there is in general no neat relationship between the standard errors of *R* and log *R*, so it needs to be approximated).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] There exist several alternatives to the Wald test, namely the likelihood-ratio test and the Lagrange multiplier test (also known as the score test).
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] Engle showed that these three tests, the Wald test, the likelihood-ratio test and the Lagrange multiplier test are asymptotically equivalent.
[src:hypothesis-testing-deep/wald-test] Although they are asymptotically equivalent, in finite samples, they could disagree enough to lead to different conclusions.
